{"html":"<section id=\"maps\">\n\t\t\t<h2>Maps</h2>\n\t\t\t<figure class=\"full-page\" id=\"illustration-138\">\n\t\t\t\t<img alt=\"Diagram showing with coloured lines the composition of various layers of snow.\" src=\"../images/illustration-138.jpg\"/>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption>Vertical section of the snow on the summit of the Col de Valpelline. <time datetime=\"1886-08\"><abbr>Aug.</abbr> 1886</time>.<br/>\n\t\t\t\tScale one inch to a foot.</figcaption>\n\t\t\t</figure>\n\t\t\t<figure class=\"full-page\" id=\"illustration-139\">\n\t\t\t\t<img alt=\"Map showing the mountains discussed in the book, along with towns, locations, and the routes followed by the author.\" src=\"../images/illustration-139.jpg\"/>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption>General route map.</figcaption>\n\t\t\t</figure>\n\t\t\t<figure class=\"full-page\" id=\"illustration-140\">\n\t\t\t\t<img alt=\"Map of the area around the Valley of Zermatt and the Central Pennine Alps. Zermatt is surrounded by peaks. Dotted lines indicate the routes followed by the author.\" src=\"../images/illustration-140.jpg\"/>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption>The Valley of Zermatt, and the Central Pennine Alps.</figcaption>\n\t\t\t</figure>\n\t\t\t<figure class=\"full-page\" id=\"illustration-141\">\n\t\t\t\t<img alt=\"Map of the area around Valpelline, Valtournanche, and the Central Pennine Alps. Dotted lines indicate the routes followed by the author.\" src=\"../images/illustration-141.jpg\"/>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption>The Valpelline, the Valtournanche, and the Central Pennine Alps.</figcaption>\n\t\t\t</figure>\n\t\t\t<figure class=\"full-page\" id=\"illustration-142\">\n\t\t\t\t<img alt=\"Map of the area around the chain of Mont Blanc, from Chamounix in the north to Courmayeur in the south. Dotted lines indicate the routes followed by the author.\" src=\"../images/illustration-142.jpg\"/>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption>The chain of Mont Blanc.</figcaption>\n\t\t\t</figure>\n\t\t\t<figure class=\"full-page\" id=\"illustration-143\">\n\t\t\t\t<img alt=\"Coloured closeup map of the Matterhorn, showing the surrounding gletschers, the Hörnli ridge, and the routes followed by the author.\" src=\"../images/illustration-143.jpg\"/>\n\t\t\t\t<figcaption>The Matterhorn and its glaciers.</figcaption>\n\t\t\t</figure>\n\t\t</section>"}